solutions.content:
In the recursive approach we'll first set our base cases that if our *head* or *head -> next* is *NULL* then we simply return the head node as we have either a *NULL* or a Single Node in the Linked List.

Now,
If the value in head Node and the next Node is equal then using a while loop we'll shift the head Node forward till the time two adjacent nodes have the same value 
(i.e. till *head -> val == head -> next -> val*).
```
/*
For example : 1 -> 1 -> 1 -> 2 -> 3 
Initially our head will point at the first Node containing the value 1.
After going through the loop the head will be pointing at the third Node that again contains 1 but the value of the next Node isn't 1 so the loop will terminate .
*/
```
At the end of the while loop it's important to notice that we'll currently be on the Node whose value was duplicated so we'll call recursion on the next value of head and update our pre-existing head. 
**head = deleteDuplicates(head -> next)**

Otherwise if the value of head and the next node are different we'll just simply update our  *head -> next* by calling recursion on it leaving our head Node preserved as it wasn't duplicated. 
 **head -> next = deleteDuplicates(head -> next)**

Finally we'll return the head Node. 
```
ListNode* deleteDuplicates(ListNode* head) {

	// Base Case
    if(!head || !head -> next){
		return head;
     }

        int flag = head -> val;
        //If head is found duplicated
        if(head -> next -> val == flag){
            while(head -> next && head -> next -> val == flag){
               head = head -> next; 
            }
            // Since head node is still the one which was duplicated calling recursion on next Node and updating current head
            head = deleteDuplicates(head -> next); 
        }

        // If head isn't duplicated
        else{
            //Leaving current head preserved and calling recursion from the next Node of list
