March 8, 2022
**Introduction**
It is a hard level algorithm. The tip is to learn how to handle multiplication and put it's precedence before "+" and "-". 

**Case study I** 
For example, if you have a sequence of 12345 and you have proceeded to 1 + 2 + 3, now your eval is 6 right? If you want to add a * between 3 and 4, you would take 3 as the digit to be multiplied, so you want to take it out from the existing eval. You have 1 + 2 + 3 * 4 and the eval now is (1 + 2 + 3) - 3 + (3 * 4). 

**Case study II**
We need to maintain the value of consecutive * result, if we want to do another * operation, just minus consecutive * result, and use that to multiply the new number.

for 1 + 2 * 3 if we want to *4, so it should 1 + 2 * 3 - 2 * 3 + 2 * 3  *  4

The following code uses the above idea to handle multiplication. Try to debug second test case and see if it is true to have -2 * 3, followed by 2 * 3 * 4. 

The following C# code passes online judge. 

```
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Text;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

namespace _228_epxression_and_operator_B
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            var test = new Program();
            var result = test.AddOperators("123", 6);
        }

        public IList<string> AddOperators(string num, int target)
        {           
            if (num == null || num.Length == 0)
            {
                return new List<string>();
            }

            var result = new List<string>();

            runDFS(result, "", num, target, 0, 0, 0);
            return result;
        }

        /// <summary>
        /// study code
        /// https://leetcode.com/problems/expression-add-operators/discuss/71895/Java-Standard-Backtrace-AC-Solutoin-short-and-clear
        /// </summary>
        /// <param name="expressions"></param>
        /// <param name="path"></param>
        /// <param name="num"></param>
        /// <param name="target"></param>
        /// <param name="pos"></param>
        /// <param name="eval"></param>
        /// <param name="multed"></param>
        private void runDFS(List<string> expressions, string path, string num, int target, int pos, long eval, long multed)
        {
            if (pos == num.Length)
            {
                if (target == eval)
                {
                    expressions.Add(path);
                }

                return;
            }

            for (int i = pos; i < num.Length; i++)
            {
                if (i != pos && num[pos] == '0')
                {
                    break;
                }

                long operand = Convert.ToInt64(num.Substring(pos, i - pos + 1));

                if (pos == 0)
                {
                    runDFS(expressions, path + operand, num, target, i + 1, operand, operand);
                }
                else
                {
                    runDFS(expressions, path + "+" + operand, num, target, i + 1, eval + operand, operand);
                    runDFS(expressions, path + "-" + operand, num, target, i + 1, eval - operand, -operand);
                    runDFS(expressions, path + "*" + operand, num, target, i + 1, eval - multed + multed * operand, multed * operand);
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

