1) **Brute Force Solution**

	-> Here, we are storing all the nodes of the linkedlist by traversing one pass
	-> To return random value with same probablity, using **rand()** function

	Time complexity : O(N) , O(1) -> getRandom() function

	Space complexity :  O(N) -> for storing elements

```
class Solution {
    private:
    vector<int> nodes;
public:
    Solution(ListNode* head) {

        ListNode *cur = head;

        while(cur)
        {
            // storing nodes into vector
            nodes.push_back(cur -> val);

            // traversing
            cur = cur -> next;
        }
    }

    int getRandom() {

        // get the size of node vector
        int size = nodes.size();

        // return rand() % size
        return nodes[rand() % size];
    }
};
```

2) **Optimal Solution**

	The idea is to pick random elements from the linkedlist with equal probability.

   **Reservoir Sampling** is the algorithm to pick some 'x' elements in list of 'n' values with equal probability.

	  **Random element with equal probablity = X(Elements need to be picked i.e rand()) / Number of nodes till we traversed i.e pos**

	For eg:

	Initilally, we have 1 nodes, let's take rand() will be 1 so random element = 1 / 1
	After that, we have 2 nodes, so random element = 1 / 2
	Likewise, ..... it goes on.

	Time complexity : O(N) , O(1) -> getRandom() function

	Space complexity :  O(1) -> for storing elements
```
class Solution {
    private:
    ListNode *copy;
public:
    Solution(ListNode* head) {

        // copying head pointer 
        copy = head;
    }

    int getRandom() {

        ListNode *temp = copy;
        int pos = 1, res;

        // traverse the linked list
        while(temp)
        {          
            // probability will be rand() / num of elements we traversed
            if(rand() % pos == 0)
                res = temp -> val;

            temp = temp -> next;
            pos++;
        }

        return res;
    }
};

```

