First approach - iterating through the list only once and storing the values into a container (I opted for an array sized to the maximum size of the list we can get).

Creation and population of the container is linear, then each random pick is constant time. Space always linear, of course

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    ListNode *nodes[10000];
    int pos = 0;
    Solution(ListNode* head) {
        // initialising random generation
        srand(std::time(nullptr));
        // storing values in the array
        while (head) {
            nodes[pos++] = head;
            head = head->next;
        }
    }

    int getRandom() {
		// extracting a random element
        return nodes[rand() % pos]->val;
    }
};
```

Alternative: we just store head, its `length` and at each random call we iterate `n` times, with `0 <= n < length`.

Space is always constant, each operation is linear (but read below!).

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    ListNode *head;
    int length = 0;
    Solution(ListNode* head) {
        // storing the original head
        this->head = head;
        // initialising random generation
        srand(std::time(nullptr));
        // updating length
        while (head) {
            length++;
            head = head->next;
        }
    }

    int getRandom() {
        // support variables
        ListNode *curr = this->head;
        int pos = rand() % length;
		// iterating pos times
        while (pos--) {
            curr = curr->next;
        }
        return curr->val;
    }
};
```

Now, because the tests are not really that great, you might "hack" your way into better performance adding one final line to the constructor: `length = min(length, 10);` - up to you ;)

