public class Solution {
    private static final char DASH = '-';

    public String licenseKeyFormatting(String S, int K) {
        S = S.toUpperCase();

        StringBuilder result = new StringBuilder();
        int count = 0;

        for (int i = S.length() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            char c = S.charAt(i);

            if (c == DASH) {
                continue;
            } else if (count == K) {
                result.append('-');
                count = 0;
            }

            result.append(c);
            count++;
        }

        return result.reverse().toString();
    }
}
```

**Thoughts before Coding**
- Since we only want uppercase letters, we can first convert our input string to uppercase
- We also need to generate a license key that has a length with at most 12,000
	- We will need to use a StringBuilder to accumulate each character
	- Strings are immutable, we do not want to be concatenating strings
- Since, our first group in our string can have a character count of 1 -> k
	- We should work from the rightmost index of our input string and move to the left
- We may need a character count variable to keep track of our current number of characters in each group
	- When our character count variable reaches K, we will append a '-'
		- Before we append a '-', we need to check if our current character that we are looking at in our input string is not a '-',
			- because what if the input string is '-12-34', and our K is 4?
				- We do not want our result to be '-1234'
	- If our current count variable equals K, we will need to reset it back to 0
- Since, we should only be using StringBuilder.append to add in more characters
	- We have to reverse our StringBuilder before returning this result
	- This is because if our input string is '-12-34', and K is 4.
		- If we start working from the back, our StringBuilder becomes 4321
			- We need to reverse 4321 to get 1234

**Answer**
- We will first convert our input string to uppercase
	- It will be a hassle to check for lowercase letters when we are iterating later
- We also will instantiate a StringBuilder to hold our final result
	- Do not forget to reverse our stringbuilder later
- We need a counter to keep track of our current count for the current group
- We will first start with iterating from the end of our input string
	- If the current character is '-', we can continue our loop
	- If our counter equals K, we have finished one group
		- We will append a '-' to our input string
		- reset our counter back to 0
	- We will append our current character
	- increment our counter
- return the reversed string from our string builder

**Gotchas**
- We do not want to prepend characters to our stringbuilder with sb.insert(0, char)
	- this is because the stringbuilder needs to copy an array to push the elements to the right to make space for our new char
	- The append method will just add another character to the end of the array without shifting all of the other characters

**What is the Time and Space complexity?**
- Time complexity = O(k) + O(k) + O(k) = O(k), where k is the length of our input string S
	- O(k) - converting our input string to uppercase
	- O(k) - iterating through our input string to find our license key
	- O(k) - reversing our string builder
- Space complexity = O(k), where k is the length of our input string S
	- O(k) - StringBuilder to hold our result

