# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Since only the first section of the key can be `<= k` we must use a way to determine ahead-of-time on how many `char` should be placed in the first section. This would be easier if we consider the `s: String` as reversed, since that way the first section become the last section, and after finish building all the sections that has `section.length == k` we can just fill the last section with what is left of the original string, since the `char` left must be `<=k`. So using a stack would an easy solution.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. We create a stack, and feed `char` from `s` to the stack, ignoring the `'-'` character.
2. We pop all the value from the stack, use `count` to keep track of how many `char` is in the given section. If `count == k` we reset `count` and insert a `'-'` to indicate a new section should start.
3. Since we used a `Stack`, the final `ans: String` order is reversed. Thus we call `ans.reversed()` and then return the final ans.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
    fun licenseKeyFormatting(s: String, k: Int): String {
        val stack = Stack<Char>()
        for (c in s) {
            if (c != '-') stack.push(c)
        }
        var count = 0
        var ans = ""
        while(stack.isNotEmpty()) {
            if (count < k) {
                ans = "$ans${stack.pop().toUpperCase()}"
                count++
            } else {
                ans = "$ans-"
                count = 0
            }
        }
        return ans.reversed()
    }
}
```

